---
import ProjectLayout from "../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro";
---

<ProjectLayout>
  {/* HERO */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-6">
      <div>
        <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">
          Robotic Arm for Automated Fiber Placement
        </h1>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 max-w-3xl">
          Simulated an automated fiber placement (AFP) workflow using a UR5e robotic arm in PyDrake,
          focusing on contact-rich control between a roller end effector and a compliant mold surface.
          The core technical contribution was an impedance-control architecture that regulates interaction
          forces while tracking a generated surface trajectory.
        </p>

        <ul class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 mt-5">
          <li class="bg-gray-900 text-white px-3 py-1 rounded-md text-sm">Python</li>
          <li class="bg-gray-900 text-white px-3 py-1 rounded-md text-sm">PyDrake</li>
          <li class="bg-gray-900 text-white px-3 py-1 rounded-md text-sm">Impedance Control</li>
          <li class="bg-gray-900 text-white px-3 py-1 rounded-md text-sm">Contact Modeling</li>
          <li class="bg-gray-900 text-white px-3 py-1 rounded-md text-sm">UR5e</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      {/* HERO MEDIA */}
      <div class="rounded-lg shadow-md overflow-hidden w-full">
        <video
          class="w-full h-auto"
          autoplay
          muted
          loop
          playsinline
          preload="metadata"
          poster="/images/afp/hero-poster.jpg"
        >
          <source src="/images/afp/hero.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
          <img
            src="/images/afp/hero-fallback.jpg"
            alt="UR5e simulated AFP roller contact demo"
            class="w-full h-auto"
          />
        </video>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* PROBLEM + MOTIVATION */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Problem & Motivation</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          Automated Fiber Placement (AFP) is a composite manufacturing process where fiber tape is laid
          along a prescribed path and compacted with a roller. The quality of layup depends heavily on
          repeatable contact force and consistent roller alignment relative to the mold surface.
        </p>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          This project focused on the control problem at the heart of AFP: tracking a surface trajectory
          while maintaining stable interaction with the mold. Unlike free-space manipulation, AFP is
          contact-rich and sensitive to surface variation, compliance, and latency in the control loop.
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>Track a path on (planar or curved) mold geometry</li>
          <li>Maintain controlled contact during compaction (roller-on-surface)</li>
          <li>Achieve compliant behavior while resisting disturbances</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <img
        src="/images/afp/afp-example.jpg"
        alt="Automated fiber placement concept diagram"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* SYSTEM OVERVIEW */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">System Overview</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          The system was implemented and validated in simulation using PyDrake. A UR5e arm was tasked
          with moving a roller end effector along a generated trajectory while interacting with a
          compliant mold surface using Drake’s contact modeling capabilities.
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>
            <span class="font-medium">Robot:</span> UR5e model running in Drake’s simulation environment
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-medium">End effector:</span> roller designed to impose and regulate contact
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-medium">Environment:</span> compliant mold surface represented as a mesh/contact geometry
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-medium">Control goal:</span> trajectory tracking + stable force interaction via impedance control
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          The architecture intentionally emphasized robust interaction behavior rather than purely
          position-based tracking, since AFP depends on consistent compaction forces and stable surface
          contact under small disturbances and modeling error.
        </p>
      </div>

      <img
        src="/images/afp/afp-simulation-environment.png"
        alt="System overview diagram: UR5e, roller, mold surface, control loop"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* TRAJECTORY GENERATION */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Trajectory Generation</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          A key part of AFP is defining a trajectory on the mold surface and maintaining a roller
          orientation consistent with compaction. The approach used here generated feasible paths by
          leveraging geometric constraints and a mold representation suitable for simulation.
        </p>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          For the planar trajectory case, the path was generated by intersecting a plane with the mold
          surface and sampling along the resulting curve. For curved molds, the same idea extends by
          describing the mold surface parametrically and producing a surface-following reference curve.
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>Represent mold surface (e.g., Bezier surface or mesh)</li>
          <li>Generate reference curve (surface intersection / parametric sampling)</li>
          <li>Compute desired pose along the curve (position + surface-consistent orientation)</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          The output of this stage is a time-parameterized reference for the end-effector pose that can
          be tracked by the controller while maintaining surface contact constraints.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <img
          src="/images/afp/trajectory-planar.png"
          alt="Planar trajectory generation visualization"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
        />
        <img
          src="/images/afp/trajectory-curved.png"
          alt="Curved mold trajectory generation visualization"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* CONTROLLER DESIGN */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Controller Design: Impedance Control</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          Because AFP is contact-rich, purely position-based control can produce unstable interaction
          forces when the robot encounters surface variation or compliance. Instead, the controller was
          designed around impedance control, which enforces a virtual mass–spring–damper relationship
          between the actual end-effector motion and the desired trajectory.
        </p>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          Conceptually, impedance control lets the robot “feel” compliant while still tracking a path.
          The controller shapes how the end effector reacts to contact forces, trading off stiffness and
          damping against tracking error and disturbance response.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-md border bg-gray-50 p-4 text-sm text-gray-700 overflow-auto">
          <div class="font-semibold mb-2">Impedance model (conceptual)</div>
          <div>
            F = M (ẍ − ẍ<sub>d</sub>) + B (ẋ − ẋ<sub>d</sub>) + K (x − x<sub>d</sub>)
          </div>
          <div class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
            where x is the end-effector position (or task-space coordinates) and x<sub>d</sub> is the desired trajectory.
          </div>
        </div>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>
            <span class="font-medium">Goal:</span> maintain stable contact forces during compaction while tracking the path
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-medium">Behavior:</span> compliance under disturbances instead of rigid position enforcement
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="font-medium">Output:</span> command accelerations/forces that drive the robot toward the reference
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          This control strategy is well-suited for roller-on-surface interactions because it reduces
          sensitivity to small geometry mismatches and promotes stable contact behavior.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <img
          src="/images/afp/impedance-block-diagram.png"
          alt="Impedance control block diagram"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
        />
        <img
          src="/images/afp/contact-force-plot.png"
          alt="Example contact force plot from simulation"
          class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* SIMULATION SETUP */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Simulation Setup (PyDrake)</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          The simulation environment was built in Drake to evaluate interaction stability and trajectory
          tracking without requiring hardware access. The UR5e model, roller end effector, and mold
          surface were integrated into a single simulation diagram with contact enabled.
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>UR5e robot model integrated into Drake’s multibody simulation</li>
          <li>Roller end effector modeled as a rigid body attached to the wrist</li>
          <li>Mold surface represented as compliant contact geometry (mesh-based)</li>
          <li>Controller integrated as part of the Drake Diagram for closed-loop simulation</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-gray-600">
          A dedicated push test was used to validate basic impedance behavior: applying a disturbance to
          the end effector and observing stable recovery and bounded interaction forces.
        </p>
      </div>

      <img
        src="/images/afp/sim-screenshot.png"
        alt="Drake simulation screenshot of UR5e, roller, and mold"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* RESULTS */}
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Results</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          The simulation demonstrated stable contact behavior under disturbance and produced force
          signals consistent with compliant interaction. The most meaningful validation was the ability
          to push the end effector away from the surface path and observe a smooth, damped recovery
          rather than oscillation or runaway force growth.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-semibold">What worked</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>Stable interaction behavior during contact-rich motion</li>
          <li>Force signals remained bounded and interpretable under disturbances</li>
          <li>Simulation architecture supported rapid iteration on control parameters</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-semibold mt-6">Limitations</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
          <li>Full end-to-end planar trajectory tracking was not fully completed within the timeline</li>
          <li>Controller tuning and simulation integration required significant ramp-up in Drake</li>
          <li>Results reflect simulation fidelity; hardware behavior will introduce additional non-idealities</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-8">
        <figure class="rounded-lg shadow-sm overflow-hidden bg-white border">
          <img
            src="/images/afp/afp-push-test-force-plot.png"
            alt="Single pass end-effector force response during push test"
            class="w-full h-auto"
          />
          <figcaption class="px-3 py-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
            Single-pass push test: detailed force response showing disturbance rejection and damped recovery.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="rounded-lg shadow-sm overflow-hidden bg-white border">
          <img
            src="/images/afp/afp-push-test-force-plot_2.png"
            alt="Full trajectory end-effector force profile"
            class="w-full h-auto"
          />
          <figcaption class="px-3 py-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
            Full trajectory execution: periodic force regulation during repeated surface contact.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* LESSONS + NEXT STEPS */}
  <section class="mb-4">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Lessons Learned & Next Steps</h2>

    <div class="text-gray-700 space-y-4">
      <p class="text-gray-600">
        The primary takeaway was that contact-rich manipulation lives or dies on interaction stability.
        The controller is not just tracking a reference; it is shaping how the robot responds to an
        environment that is never perfectly modeled. Impedance control provided a principled way to
        manage that interaction in simulation and made the system robust to small disturbances.
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600">
        <li>
          Extend from push-test validation to full trajectory execution with stable force regulation along the path
        </li>
        <li>
          Improve mold/trajectory fidelity for curved surfaces and incorporate orientation adaptation along surface normals
        </li>
        <li>
          Formalize controller tuning (gain selection, stability margins, and sensitivity to contact stiffness)
        </li>
        <li>
          Add a realistic sensing layer (force/torque sensing assumptions, filtering, and delays)
        </li>
        <li>
          Transition the architecture toward hardware execution (UR5e on real robot, calibrated frames, safety constraints)
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</ProjectLayout>